----------------------
BOOST TOGGLE INDICATOR
----------------------

A simple tray icon tool to toggle CPU boost on supported Linux systems.

This tool uses the Linux cpu-freq driver to check and control the current CPU boost status, displaying it via a GNOME tray icon. You can toggle boost with a single click â€” privilege elevation is handled via pkexec. The current boost state is saved to disk and restored on the next boot.

When the boost status is disabled, CPU frequency is limited to the base clock leading to lower temperatures and saving power. Depending on the CPU this can incur a performance hit.

CPU boost driver (cpu-freq) documentation: https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/cpu-freq/boost.txt

-------------- 
version v0.1.0
--------------

----------
changelog:
----------

 v0.1.0: - adds state saving in ~/.config/boost-toggle, restoring previous state on startup
       - verifies boost control availability at startup


--------------------------
Dependencies/requirements:
--------------------------

GNOME Shell (with AppIndicator support), libayatana-appindicator3, Python 3, and pkexec via policykit (for privilege elevation). Tested on Ubuntu with the Ubuntu AppIndicators extension enabled. Install deps via the following command:

sudo apt install python3-gi python3-gi-cairo gir1.2-gtk-3.0 \
                 gir1.2-ayatanaappindicator3-0.1 libayatana-appindicator3-1 \
                 policykit-1

-------------
Installation:
-------------
For autostart at boot:

	1. Copy boost-toggle-indicator.py to /usr/local/bin and make it executable:
		
			sudo cp boost-toggle-indicator.py /usr/local/bin/
			sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/boost-toggle-indicator.py


	2. copy "boost-toggle-indicator.desktop" to your .config/autostart directory

			cp boost-toggle-indicator.desktop ~/.config/autostart/
			
			

	Optional: 3. To make the utility searchable and executable for standard launchers
	
			sudo cp boost-toggle-indicator.desktop /usr/share/applications/


You can also just run the script directly from wherever you like.

